<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;font-size:medium;">If you read this, you WILL KNOW how the movie ends.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<br>
In a nutshell, the last two used as many stereo-typical genre movie aspects as they could cram in.  You have to watch for it, they don't have a NEOn sign flashing &quot;This is the SciFi Aspect Spoof!!&quot;, but it is there.<br>
The Neo/Smith fight scene at the end was the anime aspect spoof.  I loved the SuperNeo vs. the MegaSmith imagery, but you also have to remember something... as long as Neo lives, Smith can't be destroyed.  As long as SMith is alive, Neo can't die.  The use of the anime fighting style was, I think, purposefully done to take a man on man fight and bring it far beyond the limits fo human ability ... yet STILL SHOW that neither of these men can destroy the other.  In teh very end, Neo finally figures it out, to destroy smith, he has to LET Smith destroy him.  Smith interfaces with him, destroys Neo ... and unknowingly destroys himself.<br>
Think about it, could there be a god without a devil?  Could you have &quot;good&quot; without bad?  One relies on the other to survive, and when Neo realizes this (after Smith drives him through about 15' of concrete and he gets up unhurt), he realizes that there is only one way to destroy Smith. He has to be destroyed.<br>
His &quot;purpose', his meaning, was to destroy Smith.  If you were paying attention, you see Smith get scared (a HUMAN emotion) when Neo realizes how to destroy him.  THIS is the point when the two have traded places... Smith=Human and Neo=Machine/program.  Neo understands how to destroy him now, and knows that the only way to do it is to destroy himself.  <br>
Remember ... Neo is a creation from the machines, not from a human/human coupling.  In essence, the Oracle... or his mother... created him.  Is it too hard for you to think that maybe he was actually enabled with aspects of the machine world... making him 'the one'?  Think of how he always was able to control his environment in the matrix to a better degree than the other humans.  Think about how he was able to &quot;read&quot; the agents.  Think about how this was actually the 6th running of the matrix.  Think about how we find out that programs (and maybe machines) CAN love and create their own children.  Think about the special relationship Neo has with the oracle, and how much she seems to care for him.  Think about the Edopieous (sp?!) allusions and how proud the oracle always seemed of Neo whenever she saw him, then compare that to his feelings for  the architect.  <br>
<br>
think about it.<br>
